comment.body:
Unfortunately you haven't provided enough information to reproduce the problem. Perhaps you could clone the https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-java-skeleton and create a minimal reproducer for your problem based of that.

That said, at a glance it looks like you are sharing your `Scenario` object between scenarios. If this is the case, it would be a programming error. An error that started to matter in Cucumber v4 with the introduction of parallel execution.

There are a few ways this might happen. One would be to assign the `Scenario` to a global variable. For example:

https://github.com/cucumber/cucumber-java-skeleton
```java
package io.cucumber.skeleton;

import io.cucumber.java.Before;
import io.cucumber.java.Scenario;
import io.cucumber.java.en.Given;

public class StepDefinitions {

    private static Scenario scenario;

    @Before
    public void setup(Scenario scenario) {
        if (StepDefinitions.scenario == null) {
            StepDefinitions.scenario = scenario;
        }
    }

    @Given("I have {int} cukes in my belly")
    public void I_have_cukes_in_my_belly(int cukes) {
        scenario.log("Hello world"); // This will throw when executing a second scenario
    }
    
    ...
}
```

But if you're using a DI framework such as Spring or Guice you can do something similar by assigning the `Scenario` object to an object in the DI context that is shared between scenarios.

